{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 12:42:20.828631", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary\n- Anomaly detected: Partial network connectivity. Hosts on leaf_1 can reach each other, but any traffic involving hosts on leaf_2 or across leaves fails.\n- Fault localization: Leaf_2’s OpenFlow pipeline is dropping all traffic; Spine_1 has no forwarding rules; Leaf_1 has only per-host pair flows and no general learning/flooding. The SDN controller is connected to all switches but has not programmed the fabric correctly.\n- Probable root cause: Misprogrammed or incomplete OpenFlow rules from the SDN controller, resulting in total drop on leaf_2 and no inter-leaf forwarding via spine_1. Additionally, one physical interconnect (leaf_1:eth3 <-> spine_1:eth2) is not added to the OVS bridges, diverging from the described topology.\n\nDetailed Findings\n\n1) End-to-end reachability\n- Working:\n  - host_1_1 (10.0.0.1) ↔ host_1_2 (10.0.0.2): OK. Example: 0% loss, RTT avg ~2 ms.\n- Failing:\n  - Any traffic to/from hosts on leaf_2: host_2_1 (10.0.0.3) and host_2_2 (10.0.0.4) fail in all directions with “Destination Host Unreachable” from the source hosts.\n  - host_2_1 ↔ host_2_2 (same leaf): also fails.\nInterpretation: Leaf_2 is not forwarding even intra-leaf traffic; inter-leaf forwarding is also not occurring.\n\n2) Open vSwitch control plane and port status\n- Controller connectivity:\n  - leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1 all show Controller \"tcp:20.0.0.100:6633\" is_connected: true, fail_mode: secure.\n- Port states (OVS port-desc):\n  - All fabric-facing ports on leaf_1 (eth0/1/2), leaf_2 (eth0/1/2), and spine_1 (eth0/1) are LIVE and 10G-FD.\n  - Internal LOCAL ports are down (expected/benign).\n- Topology/bridge membership mismatch:\n  - The physical link leaf_1:eth3 and spine_1:eth2 are UP at OS level but are not added to the OVS bridges (absent from ovs-vsctl show/port-desc). This deviates from the provided topology, though other uplinks exist.\n\n3) OpenFlow pipeline inspection\n- leaf_1:\n  - Only two specific L2 flows are present:\n    - in_port=1, dl_src=72:07:9b:1f:61:3b, dl_dst=6a:c8:71:9b:b2:fc -> output:2\n    - in_port=2, dl_src=6a:c8:71:9b:b2:fc, dl_dst=72:07:9b:1f:61:3b -> output:1\n  - No table-miss rule; in fail_mode secure this means unknown/broadcast frames (e.g., ARP, unknown unicast) are dropped unless explicitly matched.\n  - Explains why only host_1_1 ↔ host_1_2 works and nothing else from leaf_1.\n- leaf_2:\n  - A single rule: priority=100 actions=drop (no other flows).\n  - This drops all traffic, including intra-leaf L2 traffic and ARP.\n  - Explains complete isolation of host_2_1 and host_2_2.\n- spine_1:\n  - No flows installed at all.\n  - With fail_mode secure, this yields a drop-by-default behavior, preventing any inter-leaf forwarding.\n\n4) Impacted traffic patterns\n- Intra-leaf on leaf_1: Allowed only for the specific host-pair MACs the controller explicitly configured.\n- Intra-leaf on leaf_2: Fully blocked due to default drop rule.\n- Inter-leaf traffic via spine_1: Blocked because spine_1 has no forwarding entries and leaf_1/leaf_2 lack learned/flooding behavior for ARP/unknown unicast.\n\nAssessment and Root Cause\n- The switches are healthy at the data-link level (ports LIVE). The management channel to the SDN controller is up (is_connected: true).\n- The OpenFlow control plane state is abnormal:\n  - leaf_2 is explicitly configured to drop all traffic.\n  - spine_1 has no forwarding rules.\n  - leaf_1 is only partially programmed for a single host pair, with no table-miss or broadcast handling.\n- Therefore, the root cause is an incorrect or incomplete SDN controller policy/flow installation across the fabric, particularly:\n  - leaf_2: enforcement of a blanket drop rule.\n  - spine_1: absence of inter-leaf forwarding rules.\n  - leaf_1: lack of table-miss and cross-leaf forwarding entries.\n- Secondary observation: the link leaf_1:eth3 <-> spine_1:eth2 is not part of the OVS bridges, inconsistent with the intended topology. While not the primary cause (other spine links exist), it reduces redundancy and may contribute to path constraints.\n\nConclusion\n- The network exhibits a control-plane programming fault rather than a physical link or host NIC issue.\n- Faulty devices (from a forwarding state perspective): leaf_2 (drop-all flow), spine_1 (no flows), and incomplete programming on leaf_1.\n- The abnormal behavior is consistent with an SDN controller misconfiguration or failure to compute/install correct OpenFlow rules for L2 bridging across the spine–leaf fabric.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 8145, "output_tokens": 3516, "total_tokens": 11661, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 6912}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2304}}}
